The Twig sandbox in Drupal blocks direct method calls on objects for security — including `entity` property access on field items. This prevents arbitrary object manipulation in templates.

**Fix: Preprocess the value in a hook_preprocess_HOOK function.**

In your module’s `.module` file:
```php
use Drupal\Core\Template\Attribute;

function mymodule_preprocess_node(&$variables) {
  $node = $variables['node'];
  if ($node->hasField('field_image') && !$node->get('field_image')->isEmpty()) {
    $image = $node->get('field_image')->entity;
    if ($image) {
      $variables['hero_image_url'] = $image->url();
      $variables['hero_image_alt'] = $image->get('alt') ?: '';
    }
  }
}
```

Then in your `node.html.twig`:
```twig
<img src="{{ hero_image_url }}" alt="{{ hero_image_alt }}" />
```

✅ Complies with sandbox restrictions
✅ Ensures alt text is safely accessed and passed
✅ Prevents exposure of entity IDs or internal methods in templates

Use `attributes` and `setAttribute()` in the preprocess function — **never hardcode aria attributes in Twig**. This ensures proper escaping and prevents injection.

In your preprocess (e.g., `hook_preprocess_node()` or `hook_preprocess_field()`):
```php
use Drupal\Component\Utility\Xss;

function mytheme_preprocess_node(&$variables) {
  $node = $variables['node'];
  $title = $node->label();

  // Safely prepare aria-label for a link.
  $aria_label = Xss::filter($title, ['a' => ['href', 'title', 'aria-label']]);
  $variables['link_aria_label'] = $aria_label;

  // Or set directly on attributes if rendering a link field:
  if (isset($variables['content']['field_link'])) {
    $variables['content']['field_link'][0]['#attributes']['aria-label'] = $aria_label;
  }
}
```

In Twig (`node.html.twig` or `field.html.twig`):
```twig
{# If rendering a field manually #}
<a href="{{ url('entity.node.canonical', {'node': node.id}) }}"{{ attributes.setAttribute('aria-label', link_aria_label) }}>
  {{ title }}
</a>
```

**Accessibility rationale:**
- SC 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value) requires accessible names for interactive elements.
- `aria-label` must be programmatically determined — static or unescaped values risk XSS and break screen readers.
- Using `Xss::filter()` + `setAttribute()` ensures safe, standards-compliant output.

✅ Avoid: `{{ '<a aria-label="' ~ node.label() ~ '">...</a>'|raw }}` — this is unsafe and violates SC 4.1.2 and 1.3.1.

Drupal recommends **skip links be rendered in the page_preprocess phase**, not directly in Twig. This ensures proper structural placement (before main content) and consistent accessibility across themes.

**Step 1: Attach the skip link in preprocess**
In `mytheme.theme`:
```php
use Drupal\Core\Render\Element;

function mytheme_preprocess_page(&$variables) {
  // Only add skip links for anonymous users or when theme allows (e.g., not admin theme).
  if ($variables['page']['#show_block_cache'] ?? TRUE) {
    // Define skip link targets: main content and navigation
    $skip_links = [
      '#type' => 'links',
      '#theme_wrappers' => ['skip_link' => ['#id' => 'skip-link']],
      '#links' => [
        'main-content' => [
          'title' => t('Skip to main content'),
          'url' => new \Drupal\Core\Url(':main'),
          'attributes' => [
            'class' => ['skip-link'],
            'data-drupal-link-system-path' => '<front>',
          ],
        ],
        'navigation' => [
          'title' => t('Skip to navigation'),
          'url' => new \Drupal\Core\Url(':nav'),
          'attributes' => [
            'class' => ['skip-link'],
            'data-drupal-link-system-path' => '<front>',
          ],
        ],
      ],
    ];

    // Attach skip links as a top-level render element.
    $variables['attributes']['id'] = 'skip-link-target';
    $variables['skip_links'] = $skip_links;
  }
}
```

**Step 2: Render in page.html.twig**
```twig
{# Place as first focusable element in <body> #}
{% if skip_links %}
  {{ skip_links }}
{% endif %}

{# Main content wrapper with appropriate ID #}
<main id="main-content" role="main" class="skip-link-target">
  {{ page.content }}
</main>
```

**Step 3: Add CSS for visible focus (a11y best practice)**
```css
.skip-link:focus {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  z-index: 1000;
  width: auto;
  height: auto;
  padding: 1rem;
  background: #000;
  color: #fff;
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

**WCAG alignment:**
- SC 2.4.1 (Bypass Blocks) — Skip links must be first focusable items and visible on focus.
- SC 2.4.3 (Focus Order) — Skip link must appear before repeated content.
- SC 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value) — Skip links must have accessible names (handled by `t()`).

✅ Never hardcode skip links in Twig without preprocess context — it risks missing IDs, wrong routing, or invalid HTML structure.

Under the Twig sandbox (enabled by default in Drupal 11 for security), **entity method calls are blocked** — including `->entity`, `->get()`, and `->alt`. This is intentional: Twig templates should *not* perform logic or access protected properties.

✅ **Correct fix: Preprocess the value in `hook_preprocess_node()`**

In `mytheme.module`:
```php
use Drupal\Core\Template\TemplateVar;

function mytheme_preprocess_node(&$variables) {
  $node = $variables['node'];
  if ($node->hasField('field_image') && !$node->field_image->isEmpty()) {
    $image_item = $node->field_image->entity;
    // Precompute alt text (or entire render array if needed)
    $variables['field_image_alt'] = $image_item ? $image_item->alt : '';
  }
}
```

Then in `node.html.twig`:
```twig
<img src="{{ file_url(node.field_image.0.entity.uri.value) }}"
     alt="{{ field_image_alt }}"
     loading="lazy" />
```

✅ Bonus: For full accessibility compliance, always ensure:
- `alt` is **non-empty** (or empty `alt=""` if purely decorative)
- Image has `loading="lazy"` where appropriate
- No `aria-label` is needed if `alt` is descriptive enough

❌ Never do this in Twig:
```twig
{# WRONG — sandbox block #}
{{ node.get('field_image').entity.alt }}
```

This pattern prevents accidental exposure of sensitive field values and enforces separation of logic from presentation.

